node.text: I am listening to your  interview with @dawn_serra on the #sexgetsrealpodcast and I cannot agree with you more! Everything you say I keep thinking to myself 'OH MY GODDESS, IS SHE READING MY MIND?!' You are an amazing beautiful STRONG (better yet SEXUALLY strong) woman! I am a bisexual woman married, almost 10 years now, to a man who I truly believe is my twin flame. I love this man dearly and can't help to put him on a pedestal and bow down to him, which, trust me when I say he truly does deserves to have the ground he walks on to be kissed! But, like every relationship, there's been some...hearts broken, trust broken and faith in us lost. There's a lot of repair needed to be done to our foundation. In the last 6 years we have turned the heat up on our kink thermometer full blast, I'm talking like blazing full blast. Which included me mustering up the courage to reveal my darkest fantasies, for example I like to be choked. I didn't even consider such a thing until I stumbled across an erotic photo of a man choking a woman while giving her a very sexy kiss full of tongue. The picture screams out "you're mine" in such a way that made my stomach do a million flips, and that's how I found out about my "being vulnerable" fetish. So I spilled the beans and told him every fantasy I ever fantasized about but I'm still having a hard time getting him to explore outside of the school girl costume because he has to have other fantasies right? But I can't get him to tell me, I would hope after 13 years together he wouldn't be too shy or embarrassed but that is the vibe I'm getting. In the meantime I am starting to fantasize more and more about sex with women. And my lust for the feeling of a woman's body in my hands keeps getting stronger and stronger. I feel as if I should tell him because we both agreed being %100 honest with each other but I don't know how to A. Tell him & B. Fulfil this STRONG urge. I've subscribed to your emails and I will be following you on Your social media accounts. Hopefully you can give me that "Ah ha!" moment that answers my questions and curiosities. I am so glad I have found you! I can't wait to soak up some of your wisdom!💙💖💜
Love this!!

If sexual liberation comes with a “should”—you should have sex multiple times a day/week/month; you should orgasm every time you have sex; you should only be able to bring yourself to orgasm without a vibrator; you should squirt; you should masturbate; your sex should only be “sacred”; you should be submissive; you should have a small number of sex partners; you should be able to get wet without the use of lube; you should have one sexual partner at a time; you should only watch “feminist” porn; you should do tantra; you should be kinky; you should be non-monogamous; you should like a specific sex act that everyone else seems to like; you should be multiorgasmic—it isn’t sexual liberation. It’s oppressive.
-
I think about this a lot because it comes up constantly in my sessions with clients. But I’ve been thinking about it even more these days because of a recent conversation I had on my podcast, The Sexually Liberated Woman, with Amy of @wildflowersex where we go in (and throw massive shade) about sex educators and teachers who tout sex-positivity and sexual liberation while giving ridiculous (and rather sex-negative) rules and restrictions about what it means and looks like to be sexually liberated.
-
But true sexual liberation doesn’t come with rules or pleasure hierarchies. True sexual liberation is about giving yourself (& others) permission to be who you are and who you want to be sexually outside of our culture’s (or a particular person’s) shoulds. It’s about fully honoring who you are as a sexual person—your needs, your desires, your preferences, your body—without apology or explanation.
-
There is not one definition or expression of sexual liberation. And if anyone tells you otherwise, especially if they’re a sex educator or they say they’re sex-positive, run.
-
I’m curious—what “shoulds” have you or others put on yourself when it comes to your sexuality & sexual expression? And how have those shoulds held you back from feeling the freedom in sex that you so desire to feel?
I’m all ears. 💖
-
PS—my podcast is called The Sexually Liberated Woman & you can find it on Apple Podcasts, Spotify, & SoundCloud. the episode with Amy is episode 33, link in bio.

@evyan.whitney I’ve gone through 4 copies, because I always gift my copy when I have a friend who is having a rough time. Best money I’ve spent. 🌟

This may seem odd, but I followed you back in your Apricot Tea days, and still do now. You talked about a book then called Entre Nous that I return to about twice a year; that book has been a godsend. I appreciate your ongoing candour and self-discovery, and thank you for a book recommendation that has served me almost 10 years. ❤️

@unknowneland oh that sexual should I am so familiar with. I actually wrote about this on my website. I think the essay is called “A Plea to Stop Saying Yes to Sex You Want to Say No to” or something like that. I don’t have the URL on hand but a quick google search with the name of my site (Sex Love Liberation) should find it! I feel this. you’re not alone. 💖
@evyan.whitney thank you 😍

Wow thank you so much for this post. A should I'm encountering these days "if there is real love, relationships should be free and open"... for a lot of time I fed into this idea too and suddenly I'm realizing that there is no should in love, that we are free to choose to share our space with one beautiful person at a time, and its not necessary that i judge myself for wanting this. Another sexual should that I'm letting go "I should have sex with my partner even though I don't feel like it, so that he feels happy and loved (aka stays with me).
This is everything and then some.
@the_girlkyle yesss! it was actually in a healing session with @drdaniellecornelius that I first heard that phrase. it’s a good one. 💞
As many therapists have said to me, don’t “should” on yourself.
Yessss
@lxwm this is so important!!!💋💋
This spoke to me ❤️
@laivinia.luna I hear you. 💖 please let me know if you need anything as you work towards freedom. 🌹
@laivinia.luna I’m right there with you babe
@evyan.whitney Thank you ❤️ somehow I missed the comment 🙈

Love love love ❤️ I'm only recently tip-toeing into self-love and sexuality and it is true I felt a lot of pressures you write about. But most shoulds come from me - I should be more open, I should try everything once, I should be submissive, I should be able to feel pleasure when with a man. There's so much, and so much is influenced by childhood programming and past traumas. I really hope to break free one day ❤️
@girlz1withcouch 💜
Exactly!!!!
Yes! The most annoying word ever esp. around sex
@jinkxproof W T F!!!! this makes me RAGE!!!!! do you remember the person so I never ever refer people to their work again? (& if you don’t wanna put them on blast, you can DM me). ugh! i’m so sorry.
@evyan.whitney I’ll find it. It may take me some time because I unfollowed the account but I’ll find it. 👊🏼

Interestingly, your post reminds me of how I felt when I read an article written by a someone who claimed to be a sexual mentor, who insisted that we all stop using our clitoris to orgasm. It was apparently a cop out we SHOULD all be aiming higher than that. 😡
♥️So important!
THISSSSS 💕✨❣️
This is so amazing and such a wonderful reminder that applies not only to sexuality, but to every facet of life’s journey in general. Thank you so much for sharing this💕

That post on your story is so wrong about the Torah or what he probably meant to say was the tenach... monogamy is absolutely taught in Judaism. The ONLY time a man is able to marry or have relations with a woman that is not their wife is if their wife cannot conceive with the permission of the wife like in the case of Abraham and Sara and then another cases if the wife’s husband dies the husband who died his brother could marry the widow’d wife (if she chooses) to the carry-on the bloodline other than those two exceptions Judaism absolutely preaches and teaches monogamy it’s one of the most sacredsacred things that two people can have together so I’m gonna go ahead and have to disagree with that statement - pure ignorance. Unless I missed something in Hebrew school, but I doubt it.
well said. i’ve worked on this with my therapist before, the “shoulds”. you are inspiring!

Your recent podcast episode "My sexual liberation is not for male consumption" had me feeling every feeling: happy, sad, angry, frustrated,  very angry & joyful. I just left a male dominated industry and am entering into a VERY male dominated industry and felt like I really needed to hear this. Just like most, I am in the midst of a huge awakening (I just fully realized I'm not bisexual, I'm gay! Yay!) and wow, this episode & podcast has really helped me start to heal my wounds. THANK YOU. ❤️
This is such a needed post and podcast. Thank you!! 💜💫💜
